  "response_text": "This is a comprehensive marathon training schedule designed for a **beginner**. The primary goal is to get you to the finish line safely and injury-free, not to achieve a specific time.\n\n**Prerequisites:** You should be able to comfortably run 3 miles (5 km) or run/walk for 30 minutes at least 3 times a week before starting this plan.\n\n**Core Philosophy: Run/Walk & Consistency**\n- **Run/Walk:** Use a ratio like run 4 minutes, walk 1 minute. This dramatically reduces injury risk and makes long runs manageable.\n- **Consistency:** Missing one run is fine. Missing two in a row is a problem. The long run is the most important workout of the week.\n\n---\n\n### The 20-Week Beginner Marathon Schedule\n\n**Key:**\n- **E = Easy Run:** Conversational pace. You can speak in full sentences.\n- **R/W = Run/Walk:** 4 min run / 1 min walk (adjust as needed).\n- **LR = Long Run:** The cornerstone of your training. Go very slow.\n- **CR = Cross-Training:** Cycling, swimming, elliptical, or brisk walking (30-45 min).\n- **Rest:** Complete rest or very gentle stretching/yoga.\n\n| Week | Mon | Tue | Wed | Thu | Fri | Sat | Sun | Total Miles (approx) |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **1** | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 4 mi LR | Rest/CR | 10 |\n| **2** | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 3.5 mi E | Rest | 5 mi LR | Rest/CR | 11.5 |\n| **3** | Rest | 3.5 mi E | Rest | 3.5 mi E | Rest | 6 mi LR | Rest/CR | 13 |\n| **4** | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 5 mi LR | Rest/CR | 11 |\n| **5** | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 3.5 mi E | Rest | 7 mi LR | Rest/CR | 14.5 |\n| **6** | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 3.5 mi E | Rest | 8 mi LR | Rest/CR | 15.5 |\n| **7** | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 9 mi LR | Rest/CR | 17 |\n| **8** | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 6 mi LR | Rest/CR | 13 |\n| **9** | Rest | 4.5 mi E | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 10 mi LR | Rest/CR | 18.5 |\n| **10**| Rest | 4.5 mi E | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 11 mi LR | Rest/CR | 19.5 |\n| **11**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 4.5 mi E | Rest | 12 mi LR | Rest/CR | 21.5 |\n| **12**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 8 mi LR | Rest/CR | 16 |\n| **13**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 4.5 mi E | Rest | 14 mi LR | Rest/CR | 23.5 |\n| **14**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 15 mi LR | Rest/CR | 25 |\n| **15**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 16 mi LR | Rest/CR | 26 |\n| **16**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 12 mi LR | Rest/CR | 21 |\n| **17**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 18 mi LR | Rest/CR | 28 |\n| **18**| Rest | 5 mi E | Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 14 mi LR | Rest/CR | 23 |\n| **19**| Rest | 4 mi E | Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 8 mi LR | Rest/CR | 15 |\n| **20**| Rest | 3 mi E | Rest | 2 mi E | Rest | **RACE DAY!** | Rest | 26.2 + |\n\n---\n\n### Critical Details for Success\n\n#### 1. The Golden Rule: The Long Run\n- **Pace:** Your long run should be **60-90 seconds per mile slower** than your easy run pace. It should feel boringly slow. Walk through all water stations.\n- **Fueling:** For runs over 60 minutes, you need fuel.\n    - *Before:* Eat a light snack (banana, toast with peanut butter) 60-90 minutes prior.\n    - *During:* Take a gel, gummy, or sports drink every 45-60 minutes. **Practice this on long runs** – do not try new fuel on race day.\n- **Hydration:** Drink water early and often. For runs over 90 minutes in hot weather, consider an electrolyte drink.\n\n#### 2. The \"Step-Back\" Weeks (Weeks 4, 8, 12, 16, 19)\nThese are **recovery weeks**. The long run is significantly shorter. This is not a sign of weakness; it is how your body rebuilds and gets stronger. **Do not skip these.**\n\n#### 3. Cross-Training (CR)\n- **Why:** Strengthens non-running muscles, improves cardiovascular fitness without impact, and reduces injury risk.\n- **Best options:** Cycling, swimming, elliptical, or a brisk 30-45 minute walk.\n- **Don't do:** Heavy weightlifting the day before a long run.\n\n#### 4. Injury Prevention\n- **Listen to Pain:** Sharp pain = stop. Dull ache = slow down or walk.\n- **Stretch & Strength:** After runs, do 5 minutes of static stretching (hamstrings, quads, calves). Do 2x/week: core work (planks, bird dogs) + glute bridges.\n- **Shoes:** Buy new running shoes 2-3 weeks before the plan starts. They last about 300-400 miles. You will likely need a second pair around Week 10-12.\n\n#### 5. Race Week (Week 20)\n- **Taper:** You are not getting fitter this week. You are resting so your legs are fresh. The desire to \"do one more long run\" is a trap. Don't do it.\n- **Carbo-Load:** Eat normal, balanced meals. The night before the race, eat a simple, familiar meal (pasta with",
